{
  "query": "How do the effects of creating short versus long flexible habitats on subtidal artificial structures compare for fish and invertebrate populations in Australia?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies in southeast Australian estuaries, both short (1-50 mm) and long (>50 mm) flexible habitats on subtidal artificial structures showed mixed effects on fish and invertebrate populations, with outcomes varying by species, survey timing, and habitat characteristics. Long flexible habitats supported macroalgae and non-mobile invertebrate or fish species that were absent from structure surfaces without flexible habitats (Action 3451). Long flexible habitats had mixed effects on fish species richness around structures, depending on fish presence when flexible habitats were created, and mixed effects on the abundance of fishes or seahorses depending on species and timing (Action 3451). For invertebrates, long flexible habitats had mixed effects on mobile and non-mobile invertebrate abundance depending on species group and survey week, with one study reporting that flexible habitats decreased mussel abundance on structure surfaces but the flexible habitats themselves supported higher biomass than structure surfaces (Action 3451). Short flexible habitats had mixed effects on mobile and non-mobile invertebrate community composition depending on density or length of flexible habitats (Action 3450). Short flexible habitats also had mixed effects on mobile and non-mobile invertebrate abundance depending on survey week, species group, and flexible habitat length, and mixed effects on seahorse abundance depending on survey week (Action 3450). Long flexible habitats were used by seahorses, while behavioral data was not available for short flexible habitats (Actions 3451, 3450).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3450",
    "3451"
  ]
}

