{
  "query": "What is the evidence base for the effectiveness of creating large protrusions or ridges (>50 mm) on subtidal artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "No studies were found that evaluated the effects of creating large protrusions (>50 mm) on subtidal artificial structures on biodiversity (Action 3443). This means no evidence exists to indicate whether or not this intervention has any desirable or harmful effects (Action 3443). In contrast, evidence exists for smaller-scale modifications: creating grooves and small protrusions, ridges or ledges (1-50 mm) was examined in three studies from marinas in northern Israel and the UK, and on an open coastline in southeast Spain (Action 3452). These smaller modifications showed mixed effects, with some studies finding altered community composition and increased species richness and diversity, while others found no increase in species diversity but mixed effects on species richness depending on surface orientation (Action 3452). Additionally, creating small protrusions (1-50 mm) alone was examined in one study in Japan, which reported mixed effects on macroalgal abundance depending on species (Action 3453). Textured surfaces (\u22641 mm) were examined in three studies from Italy, Israel, and the USA, showing variable effects on community composition, richness, and abundance (Action 3449).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3443",
    "3452",
    "3453",
    "3449"
  ]
}

