{
  "query": "What are the observed outcomes of transplanting or seeding organisms onto intertidal artificial structures in Australian estuaries?",
  "relevant_summary": "Ten studies examined the effects of transplanting or seeding species onto intertidal artificial structures, with seven studies conducted in estuaries in southeast Australia and Hong Kong (Action 3472). \n\nCommunity Response: Three studies in Hong Kong and Australia reported that oysters transplanted onto intertidal artificial structures supported macroalgae, mobile invertebrate, non-mobile invertebrate and fish species that were absent from structure surfaces without transplanted oysters (Action 3472). Three studies found that transplanting oysters had mixed effects on combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness and/or diversity on structure surfaces, depending on the site and/or the presence and size of grooves and small ridges or ledges on surfaces (Action 3472). One study in Australia found that transplanting oysters increased mobile invertebrate species richness on structure surfaces (Action 3472). Two of three studies in Australia found that transplanting oysters and/or coralline algae did not increase fish species richness on and around structure surfaces, while one found mixed effects depending on surface features and site (Action 3472).\n\nPopulation Response: Two studies in Australia found mixed effects on combined macroalgae and invertebrate abundance, depending on surface features (Action 3472). Two of three studies in Hong Kong and Australia found that transplanting oysters had mixed effects on mobile invertebrate abundance depending on surface features and/or site, with one study also finding increased non-mobile invertebrate and oyster recruit abundance and decreased barnacle abundance (Action 3472). Two of three studies in Australia found that transplanting oysters and/or coralline algae did not increase fish abundance on and around structure surfaces (Action 3472). Six of eight studies in Australia, Spain, Singapore and Hong Kong reported that survival of transplanted mobile and non-mobile invertebrates varied depending on species, site, and/or presence and size of surface features, with higher oyster survival when transplanted into grooves compared with on ridges (Action 3472).\n\nBehavior: One study in Australia found that transplanting oysters and/or coralline algae did not increase time fishes spent interacting with structure surfaces or number of bites taken, but benthic fishes took more bites from surfaces with transplanted oysters than from those with transplanted algae and oysters together (Action 3472).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3472"
  ]
}

