  "relevant_summary": "The evidence for managing human activities on intertidal artificial structures is extremely limited. For ceasing or altering maintenance activities on intertidal artificial structures, no studies were found that evaluated the effects of this intervention on biodiversity (Action 3440). Regarding harvesting management, only two studies examined the effects of managing or restricting harvesting of species on intertidal artificial structures, conducted in Italy, Gibraltar and southeast Spain (Action 3458). These studies found that restricting human access on intertidal artificial structures did not increase limpet abundance on structure surfaces, but did result in larger limpets with more balanced sex ratios compared to unrestricted structures (Action 3458). However, legally restricting human access did not prevent people from harvesting invertebrates and fishes on and around structures (Action 3458). For controlling or removing non-native or nuisance species on intertidal artificial structures, no studies were found that evaluated this intervention (Action 3439).",
