{
  "query": "To improve biodiversity on intertidal artificial structures, how do the outcomes of creating natural rocky reef topography compare to creating 'rock pools'?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence from multiple studies, creating 'rock pools' on intertidal artificial structures appears to be more effective than creating natural rocky reef topography for improving biodiversity outcomes.\n\nCreating natural rocky reef topography showed limited biodiversity benefits (Action 3435). One study found that this approach did not increase the combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness on structure surfaces, though it did have mixed effects on barnacle and mobile invertebrate abundances depending on the site. The natural topography was colonized by macroalgae and limpets, with limpets using shaded grooves and water-retaining depressions.\n\nIn contrast, creating 'rock pools' demonstrated significantly stronger biodiversity improvements (Action 3476). Across 18 studies, rock pools supported macroalgae, mobile invertebrate, non-mobile invertebrate and/or fish species that were absent from structure surfaces without pools. Nine of 12 studies found that rock pools supported higher combined macroalgae, invertebrate and/or fish species diversity and/or richness than structure surfaces without pools. Rock pools created different community compositions compared to surfaces without pools, and were used by sea slugs, urchins, octopuses, macroalgae, invertebrates and fishes.\n\nHowever, the effectiveness of rock pools varied depending on factors such as pool depth, shore level, wave exposure, and site conditions. Some studies found that created pools supported different communities compared to natural rock pools, and wave-sheltered pools could fill with sediment within two years. The evidence shows mixed effects for some measures like invertebrate and fish abundances, depending on specific conditions and species groups.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3435",
    "3476"
  ]
}

